<br>
The interpretations of Revelation and Daniel are just like hearing scientists try to explain one of their theories that has absolutely no hard evidence; only lots of guesses.  Listening to people argue about Revelation who haven't even studied the Gospels is sorta like those Holiday Inn commercials.  You know the ones... Some guy is explaining everything about this virus and how it can't get to them since they've got their suits on and they're airtight, and somebody asks him how long he's been studying the ooga-booga virus.  He answers, &quot;Well, I'm not exactly a scientist, but I did stay at a Holiday Inn last night.&quot;<br>
<br>
You guys are the same way.  You have no validity, no certification.  You can't even form conclusions and cite similarities between 2 different books of the Bible.  You can't even figure out what the context of one single text means by reading the entire chapter.  No sir, can't waste your time with the whole chapter when you only care about one text.  Of course, you make your assumptions on a religion by quoting under 20 verses or by trying to relate verses together which are talking about totally different things.<br>
<br>
Its like a level 45 druid who has solo'd their entire EQ career trying to explain that the 50+ game isn't really any different than the 1-50 game.  If you're 50+, you'd laugh at him for being a total n00b, but then you come onto a messageboard and do the exact same thing.  <br>
<br>
Funny thing about this analogy, though.  See, if the druid actually takes the time to learn how to group, and learns that he shouldn't nuke and run around trying to kite, and learns that a raid isn't nearly as fun as he thought, and learns that during said raid he has to buff and med about 90% of the time, and only gets to fight 10% of the time (if you consider healing as fighting), then his earlier opinion of the game being &quot;the same&quot; at higher levels will change.  But his &quot;knowledge&quot; will only reflect his current level, so if he's a clueless n00b, he can't understand what the next step is like... not until he experiences it himself.<br>
<br>
Wolvar, stop being a clueless n00b.  If you want to argue, go get your facts straight.  Here's some pointers in your quest for knowledge:<br>
1. the Bible doesn't read like a novel.  Its not there to entertain you, and they don't sell these things to make the author any money.  Study it, and use your brain to unwrap what its talking about.<br>
2.  even if you think its a load of crap, and don't believe it at all, its still an excellent brain exercise to practice your translation skills, your research skills, your referencing and cross-referencing skills, and your deductive reasoning.<br>
3.  don't read Revelation and Daniel unless you're prepared to talk to a ton of Bible-thumpers.  Alone you will never figure out what they're talking about, so if you can't handle being around those crazy preacher folk, don't waste your time.<br>
4.  read the gospels first, THEN start at Genesis.  Even if you aren't planning on being converted, you need to see the love of God in the gospels to understand his character (real or imagined, doesn't matter).  If you don't know his character, you won't understand why God is so vindictive in Genesis and Exodus and Joshua and Judges and Samuel, etc etc.<br>
<br>
bah, enough points.  I've wasted too much time on somebody who's going to tell me I'm &quot;better than this&quot; even though he doesn't have a clue who I am.<br>
<br>
